HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 728
By Sexton
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Roy Foster Kramer of
Vonore.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Roy Foster Kramer of Vonore; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Kramer was an exemplary public servant and consummate
professional, who will be remembered as a devout and humble man, a gifted orator, and a
generous member of the community; and
WHEREAS, an iconic athletic coach and administrator for half a century, Roy Kramer
was passionate about his work with his players, deeply understanding that it was his joy and
privilege to have influenced generations of young people throughout his career; and
WHEREAS, he began his extensive coaching career as head football coach at Hudson,
Dowagiac, Benton Harbor, and East Lansing schools, leading his teams to three Michigan high
school state championships; and
WHEREAS, in 1968, Roy Kramer became the head football coach at Central Michigan
University and earned numerous accolades, including a record of 83-32-2, an NCAA Division II
National Championship win in 1974, and the NCAA Division II National Coach of the Year award
in 1974; and
WHEREAS, while serving at Central Michigan University, he eventually led the
University into NCAA Division I competition for all sports; and
WHEREAS, in 1978, Coach Kramer was named Athletic Director at Vanderbilt
University; his transformation of Vanderbilt's athletic department was recognized nationally, and
in 1990, he was selected as Commissioner of the Southeastern Conference (SEC); and
HJR0728
010502
- 1 -

WHEREAS, during his thirteen years with the SEC, he pioneered conference expansion,
conference football championship games, and postseason playoffs for Division I football; and
WHEREAS, the Men's and Women's SEC Athlete of the Year award is presented
annually as the Roy F. Kramer Award, and in 2023, Coach Kramer was inducted into the
College Football Hall of Fame; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Kramer retired from the SEC in 2002, after which he and his wife of
more than sixty years, Sara Jo, moved back home to the foothills of the Smoky Mountains; and
WHEREAS, Roy Kramer first met Sara Jo Emert while they were students at Maryville
High School; Mr. Kramer was an athlete, Eagle Scout, and the class president, and Ms. Emert
was a pianist, cheerleader, and debate champion; and
WHEREAS, Roy Kramer and Sara Jo Emert both attended Maryville College, and Mr.
Kramer went on to serve as an officer in the United States Army during the Korean War, and
then conferred a master's degree from the University of Michigan; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Kramer was preceded in death by his wife, Sara Jo Emert, and he
leaves behind a host of family and friends; he was deeply devoted to his family and took great
pride in caring for them, always endeavoring to remain true to family values of the highest order;
and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we hereby honor the memory of Roy Foster Kramer, reflecting fondly upon
his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage
and conviction.
- 2 - 010502

BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express sympathy and offer our condolences to
the family and friends of Mr. Kramer.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
- 3 - 010502

